<html><head><meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=utf-8" /><meta http-equiv="Content-Style-Type" content="text/css" /><meta name="generator" content="Aspose.Words for .NET 13.4.0.0" /><title>The Environment, Food and Rural Affairs Select Committee inquiry on Food Security</title></head><body><div><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">Written evidence submitted by the National Federation of Women’s Institutes</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">10</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:7.33pt; font-weight:bold; vertical-align:super">th</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> December 2013. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">About the NFWI</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32.17pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The National Federation of Women’s Institutes (NFWI) </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">is an educational, social, non-party political and non-sectarian organisation. It was established to ensure that women are able to take an effective part in their community, to learn together, widen their horizons, improve and develop the quality of their </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">lives and those of their communities and together influence local, national and international affairs. The WI has some 21</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">3</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">,000 members in </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">6,5</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">00 Women’s Institutes across England, Wales and the Islands.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="2" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32.17pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The WI plays a unique role in providing women with ed</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ucational opportunities and the chance to learn new skills and take part in a wide range of activities. This ethos has guided the organisation since it was formed in 1915 with the aims of building an educated and informed civil society, and enabling women </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">to take an active part in civic life. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The first NFWI mandate was passed in 1918, and since then the organisation has accumulated a wide-ranging portfolio of policy concerns on a local, national and international level. The NFWI resolution process means tha</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">t members play a central role in defining organisational policy and bringing issues onto the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">WI</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">’s </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">national agenda.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="3" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32.17pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Since its inception, the Women’s Institute movement has been at the forefront of debate around pressure on the food system.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> The supply of food to the war-torn nation was central to the early activities of the growing WI movement in Britain</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> when it was </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">first formed</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Today</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">the WI’s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> work on securing a sustainable future for the UK’s dairy industry, recent pioneering work program</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">mes on food waste, and campaigns highlighting the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">plight of the honeybee remain close to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">m</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">embers’ hearts</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="4" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32.17pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">A key strand of the WIs current </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">public affairs </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">work is ‘The </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">WI </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Great Food Debate’ a programme of work to promote debate </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">on </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">the issue of food securit</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">y, and explore how best to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">overcome</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> some of these issues. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">re </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">is a lack of public awareness surrounding many of the challenges that will need to be</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> addressed</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> if we are to feed a growing</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> and more demanding</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> population. Furthermore many of the issues </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">cent</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ral to food and farming policy </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">can be divisive, with little common consensus on the best way forward. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">G</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">reater public engagement is key and as an organisat</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ion with</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> its</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> roots in education, the NFWI is</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> keen to play a role in facilitating debate and helping promote public engagement with some of the challenges facing the food system going forward. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">As the UK’s largest women’s membership organis</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ation, with over 6,5</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">00 WIs spread across England and Wales, in</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> rural and urban areas, WIs are </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">well</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">placed to lead on this issue and harness public dialogue.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="5" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32.17pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The NFWI’s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> response to th</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">is</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">i</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">nquiry is informed by</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> our work to date</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> and is very much from a consumer perspective – a perspective which the WI believes should, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">and will, become much more significant as we increasingly grapple with meeting our food needs and demands. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">How best to improve UK (and EU) food security, including using resources more efficiently</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="6" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32.17pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">As the Foresight report on the future of food </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">and farming sets out, a single approach will not be sufficient to meet the challenges of food security; instead, decisive action is needed on a wide front.  E</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ducation is </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">fundamental </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">to</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> ensuring that individuals can m</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ake more informed choices about what the</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">y eat, about cutting down on waste,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> and</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> about taking personal responsibility for the</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">se</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> decisions</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Ensuring </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">bett</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">er aw</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">areness of food security issues</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> will be an important first step in realising this aim. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">For the past year, the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">NF</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">WI has been running a progra</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">mme of work on food security</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> ‘The </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">WI </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Great Food Debate’ the purpose of which is to raise awareness of the issue of food security, promote public debate, and explore how some of these </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">challenges</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">can be tackled. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The WI Great Food Debate was launched in York</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> in December 2012 with a report authored by IPPR and a keynote speech by the Secretary of State for the Environment, the Rt Hon Owen Paterson MP</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">. In his speech, the Secretary of State </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">acknowledged the importance of this enhanced public dialogue</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> something </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">which</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> has been recognised by successive D</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">efra</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> Ministers. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">There is an important role to be played by individuals, but government’s role </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">is also key</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">It</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">must provide the necessary mechanisms, support and information for consumers to be able to make responsib</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">le choices</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> about the food that they eat</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">, something that we</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> know consumer</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> want</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> to be able to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">do</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.</span><a name="_ftnref1"></a><a href="#_ftn1">[1]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><a name="_ftnref2"></a><a href="#_ftn2">[2]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="7" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32.17pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">WI </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Great Food Debate has been incredibly </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">popular </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">with </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">our </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">members as well as with </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">the wider </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">public. The feedback to date has highlighted the importance of the topic as well as the lack of awareness that exists towards it. Since its launch, more than a hundred debates have been held by WI’s and Federations across England, Wales and the Islands. De</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">bates have </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">brought together </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">a range of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">expert </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">speakers from across the farming, academic, policy, retail, and charitable sector and have attracted both local and nation</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">al media coverage. A</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> debate organised by Haslington WI, Cheshire, which included a weeke</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">nd of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">events celebrating </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">food and farming, won the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">Daily Telegraph’s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">‘</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Bring Home the Harvest</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">’</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> award. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">A debate hosted by Staffordshire Federation was attended by 450</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> individuals from the community</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="8" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32.17pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The NFWI believes that educating young people about food </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">from a young age is </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">critical</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">A good grounding in cooking and nutrition will equip children and young people with skills for life and have positive knock</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">-</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">on effect in a range of government priority areas, including improving health and wellbeing and reconn</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ecting young people with the provenance of their food, while also instilling in children an appreciation of the wider value of food from an environmental and economic perspective.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> The NFWI </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">is delighted that cookery h</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">as </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">been </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">included in the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">revised </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">National</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> Curriculum</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> this year</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> It is important that government </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">works to ensure </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">the</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> deliver</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">y of</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> a cookery pro</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">gramme </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">for children which </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">delivers</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> practical cooking skills</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> alongside educati</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">on</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> on </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">health, wellbeing and sustainability. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="9" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32.17pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Building an appreciation about th</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">e provenance and value of our food is not only important in order to equip future generations with the skills that they need for living active and healthy lifestyles, it is also important for tackling the growing challenge of food security and sustainabili</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ty.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The Department for Environment </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">F</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ood</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">and Rural Affairs, in its Green Food Project conclusions, has identified the necessity of securing a future workforce in the food and drink sector </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">for maintaining </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">current levels of food production and innovation. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Agr</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">iculture used to be one of the main industries in the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">UK, but it now accounts for just 1.4% of our workforce. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Whilst this is of course a result of</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> development factors and the increased mechanisation of the farming industry, we have to remember that the agr</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">icultural sector does not only consist of farming from the traditional perspective – it also covers food science and agricultural technology. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">E</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">xpanding our expertise in these industries would equip us well, not only in the UK, but also abroad where we thes</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">e skills are extremely valuable. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">A robust curriculum which kindles interest in the food production system, and the wider economic, environmental and health impacts it has, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">is</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> essential to ensure that there are sufficient young people with the necessary skills, knowledge and awareness to attract them to a career in this sector.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="10" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">A</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">s </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">the Foresight Report on the Future of Food and Farming identified</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> empowering citizens to make i</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">nformed decisions about their food and changing consumption patterns </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">will</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> be essential if we are to secure food supplies in the future. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">In an inquiry launched following the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">publication of the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Foresight Report, the Environmental Audit Committee emphasised t</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">he need for greater engagement, awareness and education of sustainability issues. This ranged from better environmental education of school children, to expanding the science base and increasing consumer engagement.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">However, more than a year on </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">from</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> the go</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">vernment</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">’s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> respon</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">se</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> to the report</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">there </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">seem to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">have been </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">quite </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">limited efforts </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">in achieving these aims.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="11" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The NFWI</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> has worked closely with the Food Standards Agency</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> on </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">the ‘</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Let’s Cook!</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">’ project</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> using the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">‘</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Eatwell Plate</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">’</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">as a base for healthy eating, and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Waste Resources Action Programme (WRAP)</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> and Change4Life on the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">‘</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Let’s Cook Local</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">’</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> initiative. The programme was specifically set up to address an educational deficit that WRAP and the WI identified in some young parents, who were finding themselves without the know-how or community links to equip themselves with the skills for providin</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">g a nutritious and healthy diet for their new family. The projects use trained WI tutors to teach young parents how to cook nutritious, healthy food while taking into account financial, resource and time constraints. The projects have had some very positiv</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">e outcomes and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">powerfully </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">reinforce</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">d</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> the importance of teaching young people how to cook. While the Let’s Cook initiatives have been hugely successful with those individuals it has reached (more than 2,500 to date) </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">this is only</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> a small proportio</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">n of those </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">who would benefit from the programme</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">. The NFWI is in no doubt that initiatives such as Let’s Cook will still have a role to play even if cooking in school is made compulsory, in order to remedy the deficiencies </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">that a</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> lack of practical opportunity to learn</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> food education skills</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> to date</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">; however introducing compulsory cooking lessons will go some way to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">addressing this problem and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">start </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">equipping </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">some of our young people</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> with these skills</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="12" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">In a </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">week</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> when the Joseph Rowntree Foundation</span><a name="_ftnref3"></a><a href="#_ftn3">[3]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> has reported </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">that </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">mor</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">e than 13</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">million people in the UK are living in poverty, and in </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">a year in </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">which the number of people using food banks has almost tripled, food continues to be wasted at unsustainable levels. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">It is estimated that if food waste was reduced by half by 2050, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">the amount of food available today would increase by 25%.</span><a name="_ftnref4"></a><a href="#_ftn4">[4]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Many of the reasons behind food waste are already known, but </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">more effort is needed</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> to curtail this waste</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">With people shopping later and more often, and with an increase in single occupier househol</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ds, s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">upermarkets need to be persuaded to rethink their approach to selling food</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">; for example by ending the packaging of</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> fresh produce in multi-packs, meaning </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">that people have </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">to buy three or four</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> items</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">, or through the promotion of deals such </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">as ‘buy one ge</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">t one free’ on perishables</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> – although we are aware of positive steps by some retailers in this regard</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.</span><a name="_ftnref5"></a><a href="#_ftn5">[5]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> Supermarkets are quick to stress the protection that food packaging gives to products, yet this cannot be justified if this food is then being wasted at</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> consumer level. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="13" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Strict retailer standards on the appearance of fruit and vegetables can lead to 40% of edible produce being wasted.</span><a name="_ftnref6"></a><a href="#_ftn6">[6]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Following reductions in harvests last year caused by unpredictable weather, supermarkets were </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">temporarily </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">compelled to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">accept ‘wonky’ or ‘ugly’ fruit and vegetables to their shelves.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The NFWI </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">welcomed this flexibility but believed</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> that </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">this should be the</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> norm rather than the exception, with</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">the culture of perfection promulgated by supermarkets </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">neither</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> a sustainable or equi</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">table policy to be pursuing</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> in the long term</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Of course, it is not solely the responsibility of supermarkets to tackle food waste. Food waste occurs at all levels of the food chain, from production to consumption, and identifiable causes need to be followe</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">d up with positive action.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">  </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="14" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">In many ways the NFWI Let’s Cook programme and the Great Food Debate has been addressing a deficit in knowledge that should be tackled at an earlier </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">stage</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The NFWI would like to see </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">government a</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ddressing this from a younger a</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ge so that we are proactively</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> equipping young people with the knowledge and skills to be informed consumers</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">, rather than addressing it in</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> a reactive way. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">The relationship between the price of food and the cost of producing it</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="15" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The NFWI </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">supported calls </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">for the introduction of</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> the recently established independent Grocery Code Adjudicator</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> (GCA)</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">, to</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> oversee dealings between supermarkets and theirs suppliers, and</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> ensure that the Grocery Supply Code of Practice is adhered to</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">. The NFWI</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> believes that the domina</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">nce of the supermarkets has meant that for too long, producers and suppliers have not been able to operate on a level playing field and</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> will monitor the progress of the Adjudicator with interest</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="16" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">T</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">he </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">NFWI does have concerns that the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Adjudicator’s remit </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">i</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">s limited to the relationship between supermarkets and their </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">direct </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">suppliers. This means that it will no</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">t extend to the relationship between supermarkets and farmers, unles</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">s the farmer is also a supplier –</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">i</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.e. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">supplying directly to the supermarket. Neither </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">will</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> it cover the relationship between farmers and suppliers. It is </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">the NFWI</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">’</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">s understanding that problems exist in the supply chain between</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> farmers </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">and</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> those that they supply</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> and it is the NFWI’s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> hope that t</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">he</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> GSCOP and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Adjudicator’s </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">competencies</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> will eventually be extended to cover the</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">se</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> r</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">elationships</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">   </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="17" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">In 2012, the NFWI re</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">visited </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">campaign</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> on paying a fair price to dairy farmers</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> when several milk producers announced that they would cut the price they pa</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">id per litre for milk</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Global marketplaces in food mean that f</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">armers </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">are </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">often finding themselves </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">struggling to compete on an even playing field. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The difficulties that UK dairy farmers had following the collapse of the international</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> cream market last year </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">is </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">not only </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">a stark example of how global eve</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">nts can have local consequences, but also demonstrates how farmers are often</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> held at the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">mercy of food processors. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">A voluntary code</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> of practice</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> was implemented following </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">negotiations between the industry and gov</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ernmen</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">t, but as other voluntary codes (for example the previously voluntary GSCOP) </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">have demonstrated, t</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">hey are not always effective in ensuring that </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">producers</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> are being adequately recompensed for their work. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">W</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">h</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ere problems are </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">identified in</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> the market, the</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">se </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">must </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">be addressed through robust mechanisms, such as the GCA.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">  </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">How food and farming supply chains, and the current systems for traceability, can con</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">tribute to increased resilience.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="18" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Since 2010, the NFWI has campaigned for better country of origin l</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">abelling</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> for meat, poultry and fish products. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">COOL is p</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">articularly important for</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> the</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> UK farming industry</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">, which is</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> competing </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">with cheap imports from the EU and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">rest of the world, and with </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">farmers who do not always have</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> the</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> same animal welfare standards</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> as </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">those </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">in </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">UK</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">While premium lines may champion British meat, value cuts and ready meals often contain cheaper imported meat. Furthermore, as COOL rules currently operate, some of these products can be labelled as British if the ‘last significant cha</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">nge’ was undertaken in the UK. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">By not clearly defining what is or isn’t British, consumers are unable to compare ‘like for like’ and make informed choices about the food they eat. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">This is despite consumers saying that they would </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">like to know the country of</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> origin of the product they are buying</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">– for example </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">98% of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">WI members</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> surveyed </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">in 2010 </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">said that all products should </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">carry a country of origin label</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">. The consequence of this is that </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">many British farmers are struggling</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> financially</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">, forcing some out of the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">industry,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> and</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> leaving others unable to innov</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ate. This </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ultimately </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">poses a </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">threat</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> to</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> the long-term productivity and sustainability of British agriculture.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="19" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">In 2011, the European Parliament voted in favour of extending country of origin labelling (COOL) to a</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ll fresh meat products. The European Commission’s impact assessme</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">nt is due to report imminently</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">the NFWI </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">hopes that a robust approach to country of origin labelling is maintained. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> Following the horsemeat scandal earlier this year, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">the importance of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">fo</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">od traceability </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">consumers</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> has been demonstrated</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">, with many wanting to know where their food has come from and how far it has travelled. Whilst the NFWI acknowledges that COOL would not remove fraudulent practice by unscrupulous individuals, it would </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">be an important step towards increasing </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">transparency in the food chain, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">restoring </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">consumer confidence and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">enabling </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">consumers to make more responsible choices about the food that they eat. It would also incentivise producers to scrutinise the way that they </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">operate and simplify their supply chains in response to consumer demands.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Whether climate change risks are adequately incorporated in UK food se</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">curity strategies and planning.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="20" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Since ‘Food 2030’ was </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">set aside</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> by the coalition government, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">it has not been </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">clear</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> what the government’s firm </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">plan for food security </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">is. To</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> date, Defra’s discussions appear to have </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">largely </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">been </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">focused on increasing food production through </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">‘</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">sustainable intensification</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">’</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> – </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">including the</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">use of GMOs and more intensive farming. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">T</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">he NFW</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">I believes that a strong cross-departmental framework is needed, encompassing all levels of the production, supply and consumption chain</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> – including aspects such as health and nutrition</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">, and taking into account expert advice from policy makers </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">and scientis</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ts</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">. Whilst</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">to an extent, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Defra’s </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Green Food project</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> seeks to do this </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">– </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">and the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">NFWI and several other organisations</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> have</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> had the opportunity to</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> input into the sustainable consumption strand of this project</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> – </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">the NFWI does not believe that it presents a su</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">fficiently joined up or detailed approach, neither</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> has </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">it</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> been </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">made </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">c</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">lear what the next steps</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> for the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">project </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">will be</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The NFWI has been pleased to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">contribute to</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> the Green Food Project</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">look</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> forward</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> to hear</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ing</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">about how </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">some </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">of the outcomes from the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">project will be used in the future</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> to create a comprehensive and wide-reaching strategy. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="21" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Since 2009, the WI has been highlighting the importance </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">that </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">our honeybees and other pollinators </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">play</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> not only in</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> food production but also </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">to the</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> wider environment</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The State of Nature report published earlier this year show that we are already experiencing severe reductions in biodiversity</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">. T</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">his could</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> have serious consequences for food production in the future. Pollination by bees ensure</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> that our food choices are </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">varied and nutritious</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">, whilst </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">also </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">providing</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> incredibly efficient pollination services to farmers. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">It is hoped that</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">the government’s National Pollinator Strategy, to be published early next year, will be an important step forward in ensuring that bees are </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">afforded the protection they deserve in the future. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">However, t</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">he NFWI is concerned that the current focus of addressing food security </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">does not give sufficient weight to the importance of biodiversity and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">is weighted towards a food system which concentrates</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> on increasing production rather than promoting sustainability. Whilst increasing production is an important facet of addressing our food security needs, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">if ecosystem services are not given sufficient</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">status, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">this could be to the detriment of our natural c</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">apital in the long term. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="22" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The practical effects of climate change have been evinced in recent extreme weather events which farmers, not only in UK, but globally</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> have had to contend with. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The impact of climate change is recognised in several policy docu</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ments, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">setting out the key strategic challenges faced by the UK.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">H</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">owever</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> the NFWI is disappointed that </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">this isn’t being matched </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">with an </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">equivalent </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">degree</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> of</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> action</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">not only anticipate how we deal with the impact of climate change</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> for farmers, but </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">more </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">importantly </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> mitigat</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">e and prevent </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">the threat </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">of climate change </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">by cutting CO2 emissions.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> In 2008, the main political parties of the UK were united in passing the Climate Change Act. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">However</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> despite public</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">recognition of the threat that climate change poses, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">we are concerned </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">about potential </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">future dilution of commitment</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> to address climate change. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">F</span><a name="_GoBack"></a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">uture proofing the environment for the wellbeing of generations</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> to come should be a priority area for the UK go</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">vernment</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">, building on the reputation of the UK as a country that leads and innovates in this area.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> In turn,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Defra should be making a strong case for tackling climate change in order to protect farmers, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">environment</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> and</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> food in the future. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span 